‘It’s unbelievable,’ admitted Begiristain, who left his position as director of football at the Nou Camp to join City in 2012.

‘We don’t need to come to the draw because it’s the same every time. We faced Bayern Munich and CSKA Moscow in the group phase and now we have to deal with Barcelona again, like last season.’

This time there is an added twist, the first time English football has seen Luis Suarez since the forward quit Liverpool in the summer for £75million. It is dreamy stuff and the presence of Suarez, who scored 31 times for Liverpool in their battle with City for last season’s Barclays Premier League, guarantees an edge to the two fixtures.

Suarez has got off to a slow start at the Nou Camp following his ban for sinking his teeth into Giorgio Chiellini at the World Cup, but had great success in England and he will be a real danger.

